          "body": "Ephraim's response to the Canaanite presence in Gezer was not to renew the effort to expel them but to domesticate them: 'they became forced laborers.' The Hebrew word *mas* is the same term used for the oppressive labor gangs Israel served under in Egypt (Exodus 1:11). The theological irony is devastating. Israel, freed from *mas* by God's redemptive act at the Exodus, now imposes *mas* on the very people they were commanded to expel. They have reproduced the exploitative institution of their own oppression rather than obeying the divine command. This is not a neutral administrative decision — it is a theological regression. Judges 1:29 echoes this verse almost verbatim, placing Ephraim's failure within the larger pattern of incomplete conquest that defines the transition from Joshua to Judges. The failure at Gezer is not Ephraim's alone; it is the prototype of a national habit."
