          "title": "'To this day' — the permanent consequence of partial obedience (v. 10c)",
          "body": "The chapter closes with the narrator's timestamp: 'to this day.' The Canaanites of Gezer are still there — not as conquered vassals successfully integrated, but as an unremedied presence that persists from Ephraim's failure into the narrator's own moment. The phrase *ad hayyom hazzeh* appears repeatedly in Joshua as an authorial marker identifying things still visible, still present, still unremedied (cf. 4:9; 5:9; 6:25; 7:26; 9:27). In most cases, it marks a permanent memorial of God's faithfulness. Here it marks the permanent residue of human disobedience. The contrast with the other uses is itself a theological comment: what God plants lasts for good; what men leave in disobedience also lasts — but for judgment. The inheritance theology of the Old Testament is not merely about receiving what God grants; it is about stewarding the grant with the obedience it requires. Ephraim received in full; Ephraim obeyed in part; and the partial obedience became permanent compromise."
